How To Read Books With Data

This markdown includes questions about dickens’ books

1- most used top 20 words in dickens’ books

dickens_novels<-gutenberg_download(c(98,1023,917,766,821,786,963,1400,730,883,564,700,968,580,967))

words <-
  dickens_novels%>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text, token='words')
words<-words%>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = 'word') 

top20 <-
  words%>%
  filter(! is.na(word))%>%
  group_by(word)%>%
  dplyr::count()%>%
  arrange(desc(n))%>%
  ungroup()%>%
  mutate(top= seq_along(word))%>%
  head(20)


ggplot(top20,aes(x = -top,y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity',fill="#ca3040") +
  geom_text(aes(y = n+50, label = word), hjust = "left") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(legend.position = 'none',
        axis.text.x = element_text(hjust = 1),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        axis.text.y = element_blank())+
  labs(x='words')

2- wordcloud of dickens’ books

novels_cloud <-
  words%>%
  group_by(word) %>%
  dplyr::count() %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  slice(1:200) %>%
  select(word,freq = n) %>%
  wordcloud2(size = 1,
             color = "random-dark",
             minRotation = pi/2, maxRotation = -pi/2, minSize = 10,
             rotateRatio = 1,figPath = "cd.png")

novels_cloud

3- five most used names in dickens’ books

dickens_novels<-dickens_novels%>%
   group_by(gutenberg_id)%>%
   mutate(book=first(text))%>%ungroup()
words <-
  dickens_novels%>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text, token='words',to_lower = FALSE)
names<-words%>%
  filter(str_detect(word,"[A-Z][a-z]+"))%>%
  filter(!(str_to_lower(word) %in% words$word))%>%
  filter(word!="Mr" & word!="Mrs")%>%
  group_by(book,word)%>%
  summarise(num=n())%>%
  arrange(book,num)%>%
  top_n(5)

ggplot(names,aes(x = word,y = num, fill = book)) +
  geom_col(stat = 'identity') +
  facet_wrap(. ~ book,nrow = 3,scales = "free") +
  geom_text(aes(label = word),hjust="left")+
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,max(names$num)*2))+
  theme(legend.position = 'none',
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.text.y = element_blank())

4-emtion (positivity and negativity in words) time series in les miserables

les_miserables<-gutenberg_download(135)
words <-
  les_miserables%>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text, token='words')

emotion<-words %>%
  dplyr::mutate(order = row_number()) %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  mutate(index = floor(order/max(order)*200)) %>%
  group_by(index ,sentiment) %>%
  dplyr::count()%>%
  tidyr::spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(sentiment = positive - negative,negative=-negative)

ggplot(emotion, aes(x=index)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",aes(y=positive,fill="positive"))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",aes(y=negative,fill="negative"))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",aes(y=sentiment,fill="sentiment"))+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#ca3040","#bbbbbb","black"))

5- most used verbs for men and women in dickens’ books

words <-dickens_novels%>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text, token='words')

women<-words%>%
  filter(lag(word)=="she" |lag(word)=="She")%>%
  group_by(word)%>%
  count()%>%
  arrange(-n)%>%
  head(20)%>%
  mutate(gender="women")

men<-words%>%
  filter(lag(word)=="he" |lag(word)=="He")%>%
  group_by(word)%>%
  count()%>%
  arrange(-n)%>%
  head(20)%>%
  mutate(gender="men")

verbs<-rbind(women,men)

ggplot(verbs,aes(x = word,y = n, fill = gender)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', col = "transparent") +
  geom_text(aes(y = n+50, label = word), hjust = "left") +
  facet_wrap(. ~ gender) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(y = NULL, x = NULL)+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(legend.position = 'none',
        axis.text.x = element_text(hjust = 1),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        axis.text.y = element_blank())

6-unigram vs bigram distributions in charles dickens books

library(tidyr)
chapters<-dickens_novels%>%
  unnest_lines(line,text)%>%
  group_by(book)%>%
  mutate(chapter = cumsum(str_detect(line, regex("^[IVX]+\\. |^[ivx]+\\. |^CHAPTER [IVX]+ |^CHAPTER [ONETWHRFUVSIXG]+|^chapter [ivx]+|^chapter \\d|^chapter [onetwhrfuvsixg]+"))))%>%
  group_by(book,chapter)%>%
  filter(n()>50)%>%
  summarise(text = paste0(line, collapse = " "))

6- unigram and bigram distribution for each chapter of each dickens’ books

unigrams_per_chapter<-chapters%>%
  unnest_tokens(unigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 1)%>%
  group_by(book,chapter)%>%
  count(unigram)%>%
  separate(unigram, c("word"), sep = " ")%>%
  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word)

freq_rank_unigram_per_chapter<-unigrams_per_chapter%>%  
  group_by(book,chapter)%>%
  arrange(n)%>%
  mutate(frequency=n/n(),rank=last(row_number())-row_number())%>%
  arrange(book,chapter,rank)

bigrams_per_chapter<-chapters%>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2)%>%
  group_by(book,chapter)%>%
  count(bigram)%>%
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ")%>%
  filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word) %>%
  filter(!word2 %in% stop_words$word)
  
  
freq_rank_bigram_per_chapter<-bigrams_per_chapter%>%  
  group_by(book,chapter)%>%
  arrange(n)%>%
  mutate(frequency=n/n(),rank=last(row_number())-row_number())%>%
  arrange(book,chapter,rank)

freqs_by_chapter<-
  rbind(freq_rank_bigram_per_chapter%>%select(rank,frequency,book,chapter)%>%mutate(ngram="bigram"),
        freq_rank_unigram_per_chapter%>%select(rank,frequency,book,chapter)%>%mutate(ngram="unigram"))

freqs_by_chapter<-freqs_by_chapter%>%
  mutate(book=str_trim(book))
ggplot(freqs_by_chapter,aes(rank,frequency,color=ngram))+
  geom_point()+
  scale_x_log10()+
  scale_y_log10()+
  facet_wrap(~book,nrow = 5)

## 6-unigram and bigram distribution of every chapter of austin’s books we can say that the unigram and bigram distribution (more or less) stays the same

austin_novels<-gutenberg_download(c(105,121,141,158,161,1342,21839,42671))
austin<-austin_novels%>%
   group_by(gutenberg_id)%>%

  unnest_lines(line,text)%>%

  group_by(book,chapter)%>%

  count(unigram)%>%

  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word)
